Ironman 2019

Introduction

  • This data set looks at the 2019 Ironman World Championship Results which took place in Kona, Hawaii.

  • The data is divided into multiple columns which shows each of the 2,434 participant’s individual times for swimming, cycling and running as well as their overall times and how they rank in comparison to the other competitors.

  • The data was collected and compiled together by a UK triathalon training company known as Coach Cox.

  • We will be examining multiple questions for this data including:
    1.) Performance of Male Athletes vs. Performance of Female Athletes
    2.) How Different Nationalities Fared
    3.) Comparing the Multiple Divisions the participants were divided up into
    4.) Having A Closer Look at the Times for Swimming, Cycling and Running.

Author’s Statements
* I Ben Butler had primary responsibility for the material in the Gender Comparison Section.

  • I Rose Maria George had primary responsibility for the section looking at the different countries involved.

  • I Lida Elsa Chacko had primary responsibility for the material in the section involving how the athletes were divided up by division and what age category performed best.

  • I Sahil Singh had primary responsibility for looking into how the best athletes performed in the various stages of the ironman, as well as having a deeper look into the transition times.

Packages Used
The following packages were used in the project:

  • Tidyverse
  • Lubridate

Variables in the Data
The following variables were recorded for each observation:

  • BIB (Unique number given to every runner)
  • Name (Athletes’ Name)
  • Country (Country they represented)
  • Gender (Whether they were Male or Female)
  • Division (The age and gender bracket they were competing in)
  • Swim (The time it took to complete the swimming stage)
  • Bike (The time it took to complete the cycling stage)
  • Run (The time it took to complete the running stage)
  • Overall (The overall finishing time)
  • Division.Rank (Where the athlete ranked in their respective division)
  • Gender.Rank (Where the athlete ranked in their respective gender)
  • Overall.Rank (Where the athlete ranked Overall)
  • T1 (The time it took between finishing the swim and starting the cycling)
  • T2 (The time it took between finishing the cycling and starting the run)

Data Preperation
To analyse the times in R properly, the columns, ‘Swim’, ‘Bike’, ‘Run’ and ‘Overall’ had to be converted into numeric characters using the function called “StringToMinutes” which takes the format HH:MM:SS and converted it into minutes only.

# Defining function to convert string to integer minutes
StringToMinutes <- function(s)
  unlist(
    lapply(
      str_split(s,":"),function(s)
        sum(as.numeric(s)*c(60,1,1/60))
    )
  )

# Apply function to all time columns and look at data again
ironman$Swim <- StringToMinutes(ironman$Swim)
ironman$Bike <- StringToMinutes(ironman$Bike)
ironman$Run <- StringToMinutes(ironman$Run)
ironman$Overall <- StringToMinutes(ironman$Overall)

# Separate the data into males and females

            filter(Gender == "Male") |>
            select(-Gender, -Division, -Country,-Division.Rank)

# Getting the fastest, slowest and average male overall time
fastest_man <- min(males$Overall, na.rm = TRUE)
average_man <- mean(males$Overall, na.rm = TRUE)
slowest_man <- max(males$Overall, na.rm = TRUE)

# Getting the fastest, slowest and average female overall time
fastest_woman <- min(females$Overall, na.rm = TRUE)
average_woman <- mean(females$Overall, na.rm = TRUE)
slowest_woman <- max(females$Overall, na.rm = TRUE)

# Ratio comparing the fastest of each gender 
Ratio_F_S <- abs(fastest_man-slowest_man)/abs(fastest_woman-slowest_woman)
Ratio_F_A <- abs(fastest_man-average_man)/abs(fastest_woman-average_woman)

# Table to put all the information together
RatioTable <- matrix(c(fastest_man, average_man, slowest_man,
                       abs(fastest_man-slowest_man),
                       abs(fastest_man-average_man),
                       Ratio_F_S, Ratio_F_A, 
                       fastest_woman, average_woman, slowest_woman,
                       abs(fastest_woman-slowest_woman),
                       abs(fastest_woman-average_woman),
                       1/Ratio_F_S, 1/Ratio_F_A), ncol = 7, byrow = TRUE)

colnames(RatioTable) <- c('Fastest', 'Average', 'Slowest',
                          'Diff.Fast/Slow', 'Diff.Fast/Average', 
                          'Ratio.Fast/Slow', 'Ratio.Fast/Average')

rownames(RatioTable) <- c('Males', 'Females')

How Different Countries Fared

In this section we will examine which nationalities performed the best at the 2019 Ironman

# Gets the Top 10 countries with the most competitors
top_10 <- ironman %>%
  group_by(Country) %>%
  summarise(participants = n()) %>%
    mutate(Percentage_of_Participants =
           participants/length(ironman$BIB)*100) %>%
  arrange(desc(participants))

However since the question about gender has already been discussed, in this section we will ignore segregation by gender and focus on their age and if they are a professional or not. First the data needs a new variable to represent what division they are in.

As expected, the professionals had the lowest average time, with 30-34 year olds having the best average time for amateurs, while the older crowd were down near the bottom of the spectrum.
However at the top of the graph we see 85-89 with zero minutes. This is because the one participant in that category sadly didn’t finish. This begs the question: was there a correlation between your age and whether or not you finished the race? To answer that we need a subset of the data of people with no Overall time.

# Seeing if there is a correlation between age and if you finished the race or not
ironman |>
  group_by(Age) |>
  mutate(total = n()) |>
  filter(is.na(Overall)) |>
  mutate(num = n()) |>
  mutate(ratio = num/total) |>
  distinct(Age, .keep_all = TRUE) |>
  select(Age, total, num, ratio) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = Age, y = ratio, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(color = 'blue') +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Age Bracket", y = "Percentage of People That Did Not Finish",
       caption = "Line increases as Age increases")

From the graph there is an increase in the percentage of people that did not finish the race at 70+. 100% of people didn’t finish the race that were in the 85-89 bracket, although there was only one person who competed in that category. It is also interesting to note the high percentage of professionals that didn’t complete the race.

Comparing Swim, Bike, and Run Times

The final question asked was how did the athletes compare for Swimming, Cycling and Running. Because it would be too difficult to compare them all, let’s take a subset of the Overall ten best athletes and compare how they ranked across the three stages of the ironman.

# Ranking Top 10 athletes across all stages or ironman
ironman |>
  mutate(Swim.Rank = rank(Swim, ties.method = "first")) |>
  mutate(Bike.Rank = rank(Bike, ties.method = "first")) |>
  mutate(Run.Rank = rank(Run, ties.method = "first")) |>
  arrange(Overall) |>
  slice(1:10) |>
    ggplot() +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x=factor(Name, levels = Name),
                             y = Swim.Rank,color='Swim'), size=2.5) + 
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x=factor(Name, levels = Name),
                             y = Bike.Rank,color='Bike'), size=2.5) +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(x=factor(Name, levels = Name),
                             y = Run.Rank, color='Run'), size=2.5) +
    labs(x = "Top 10 Athletes", y = "Sport Rank", color = "Sport", 
         caption = "Top 10 Overall Athletes from Left to Right") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 75, vjust = 1.3, hjust = 1.5))

From the graph it is interesting to see how high the athletes outside of the top 2 fared in the Swimming leg of the ironman. Espcially the 9th place competitor, Bart Aernouts, how well he recovered from ranking over 185th in the Swim leg, to finish 9th overall.

Transition Times The athletes were also timed between their transition from the swim to the bike (T1) and from the bike to the run (T2). To analyse these times, a conversion into seconds makes the most sense as these times are small.

my_time_hms1 <- hms(ironman$T1) 
## Warning in .parse_hms(..., order = "HMS", quiet = quiet): Some strings failed to
## parse, or all strings are NAs
my_time_hms2 <- hms(ironman$T2)
## Warning in .parse_hms(..., order = "HMS", quiet = quiet): Some strings failed to
## parse, or all strings are NAs
T1_time_seconds <- period_to_seconds(my_time_hms1)
T2_time_seconds <- period_to_seconds(my_time_hms2)

plot(T1_time_seconds, xlab = "Athletes", ylab = "Transition Time (sec)",
     main = "Transition Times Between Swim and Bike")

plot(T2_time_seconds, xlab = "Athletes", ylab = "Transition Time (sec)",
     main = "Transition Times Between Bike and Run")

When comparing the two graphs above one thing to note is that the second transition time seemed to take longer for more athletes, possibly due to the fatigue that was starting to set in going into the final stage of the ironman. This is further proved when you look at the mean of the two transition times:

print(paste("The average for T1 in seconds is:", mean(T1_time_seconds, na.rm = TRUE)))
## [1] "The average for T1 in seconds is: 297.88057798555"
print(paste("The average for T2 in seconds is:", mean(T2_time_seconds, na.rm = TRUE)))
## [1] "The average for T2 in seconds is: 355.782854656223"

Conclusion

Upon extensive analysis into the 2019 Ironman Championships multiple conclusions can be drawn:

  • More males took part in the event than females

  • Men had a better Overall time on average, however the fastest female had a better time when compared to the average than the fastest male

  • USA and Germany were the countries with the most competitors representing them

  • When considering any number of participants, Peru had the best overall average time, albeit they only had 1 participant, with Bulgaria having the worst overall average time but again with only 1 participant

  • However, when considering countries with 50 or more participants, Spain had the best overall average time per country, with Japan having the worst time

  • When comparing divisions, M45-49 had the most competitors in it, while M85-89 had the least amount

  • These age categories hold true when disregarding the gender too (45-49 with the highest, 85-89 had the lowest)

  • As expected, the Professionals had the best overall time on average with 30-34 year olds having the best amateur time. This makes sense as 30-34 is still young enough to not be experiencing the affect of age while it is also old enough to have experience competing in other Ironman Championships

  • Only one age category did not have a finishing time which was the 85-89 bracket. When investigated further, it turns out there is a correlation between how old you are and how likely it will be if you will finish the race.

  • For the Top 10 overall athletes, many seemed to rank lower down in the Swim leg, only to make it up in the Cycling and Running portion of the Ironman. This is probably due to swimming engaging many different muscles in the body which gives it more of a level playing field, while cycling and running engage the legs and the lungs more so.

  • The males outperformed the females in every sport and when comparing the average times for each, the swim times had the smallest time difference while the cycling times had the largest time difference

  • Transition times were relatively short across the board, save for a few outliers but the transition time between the Bike and Run was generally longer than between Swim and Bike, which was more than likely due to fatigue.
